Volatile, and the java virtual machine memory model.

Without volatile, the compiler and the central processing unit are allowed to cache field reads in registers or in per core caches indefinitely. Two threads can disagree about the value of a plain field forever. The volatile keyword on a field forces every read to come from main memory and every write to flush to main memory. It establishes a happens before relationship between writes and reads of that field. Volatile does not, however, make compound operations atomic. A field declared volatile int x, with the line x plus plus, is still racy, because the increment compiles to read, add, write, and another thread can squeeze in between the read and the write. Use volatile for simple flags like a boolean shutdown signal that one thread sets and another reads. Reach for Atomic Integer or Atomic Reference whenever you actually need to update a value concurrently.
